{"query": "How do long-term and temporary fishery closures compare in their effects on marine fish abundance?", "summary": "Based on the evidence from fishery closure studies, long-term and temporary fishery closures show markedly different effects on marine fish abundance. Long-term fishery closures demonstrate mixed but generally more substantial effects on fish populations. According to action 2655, two site comparison studies found higher abundance of only one of seven fish species and lower abundance of monkfish in areas closed to groundfish fisheries for six to eight years compared to open areas. Additionally, one of two replicated before-and-after studies found more young salmon and similar numbers of older salmon returning to rivers in the five years after long-term closure of a commercial coastal fishery, while another study found lesser sandeel biomass and density peaked but showed no overall increase in the three years after a long-term fishery closure.

In contrast, temporary fishery closures show limited effectiveness for marine fish abundance. Action 2664 reports that one before-and-after, site comparison study found no increase in the biomass of the spawning stock of cod following a temporary fishery closure compared to fished areas over nine years. Similarly, the same study found no change in cod survival or length composition following temporary fishery closure compared to fished areas. However, temporary closures did provide some benefits in terms of fishing effort reduction, with action 3815 showing that move-on rules for temporary closures reduced overall cod discards and fishing effort.

The evidence suggests that long-term closures are more likely to produce measurable changes in fish abundance, though effects vary by species and are not universally positive. Temporary closures appear to have minimal direct impact on fish abundance but can provide short-term protection and reduction in fishing pressure.", "action_ids": ["2655","2664","3815"]}

